===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|trumpette|lang=enm}}, {{term|trompette||trumpet|lang=enm}} from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|trompette||trumpet|lang=fro}}, diminutive of {{term|trompe||horn, trump, trumpet|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|frk|en}} {{term/t|frk|*trumpa}}, {{term/t|frk|*trumba||trumpet}}. Akin to {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|trumpa|lang=goh}}, {{term|trumba||horn, trumpet|lang=goh}}, {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|tromme||drum|lang=dum}}, {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|trumme||drum|lang=gml}}. More at {{l|en|drum}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈtɹʌmpɪt/}}
* {{audio|En-us-trumpet.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[musical instrument]] of the [[brass]] family, generally tuned to the [[key]] of B-flat.
#: ''The royal herald sounded a '''trumpet''' to announce their arrival.''
# In an [[orchestra]] or other musical group, a [[musician]] that plays the trumpet.
#: ''The '''trumpets''' were assigned to stand at the rear of the orchestra pit.''
# The [[cry]] of an [[elephant]].
#: ''The large bull gave a basso '''trumpet''' as he charged the hunters.''
# {{context|figurative|lang=en}} One who praises, or propagates praise, or is the instrument of propagating it.
#: {{rfquotek|Shakespeare}}
#* Dryden
#*: That great politician was pleased to have the greatest wit of those times {{...}} to be the '''trumpet''' of his praises.
# A [[funnel]], or short flaring [[pipe]], used as a [[guide]] or [[conductor]], as for [[yarn]] in a [[knit]]ting [[machine]].

